 specific to the parties and distinct legal systems involved. Pol Antràs examines the contractual frictions that arise in the international system of production and how these frictions influence the world economy.Antràs discusses the inevitable complications that develop in contract negotiation and execution. He provides a unified framework that sheds light on the factors helping global firms determine production locations and other organizational choices. Antràs also implements a series of systematic empirical tests, based on recent data from the U.S. Customs and Census Offices, which demonstrate the relevance of contractual factors in global production decisions.Using an integrated approach, Global Production is an excellent resource for researchers, graduate students, and advanced undergraduates interested in the inner workings of international economics and trade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aForeign trade regulation. 0aInternational trade. 0aProduction (Economic theory). 0aSupply and demand. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Macroeconomics.2bisacsh  aMelitz model.  aU.S. imports.  acontract enforcement.  acontracting assumptions.  acontracting considerations.  acontracting institutions.  acontracting.  acontracts.  acontractual frictions.  acontractual incompleteness.  acontractual relationships.  across-industry variation.  aempirical literature.  aempirical tests.  aexport behavior.  afirms.  aglobal production networks.  aglobal production.  aglobal sourcing model.  aglobal sourcing.  aglobalization.  aimperfect-contracting variants.  ainternalization theories.  ainternalization.  ainternational economics.  ainternational trade flows.  ainternational trade.  alegal systems.  amodel-based empirical tests.  amodern workhorse models.  amul